<div class="hgroup"><h1 class="title"><span class="title">
    Simulate a right mouse click
  </span></h1></div>
<div class="region">
<div class="contents">
<p class="p">
    You can right-click by holding down the left mouse button. This is useful if 
    you find it difficult to move your fingers individually on one hand, or if 
    your pointing device only has a single button.
  </p>
<div class="steps"><div class="inner"><div class="region"><ol class="steps">
<li class="steps"><p class="p">Click the <span class="em">system menu</span> <span class="media"><span class="media media-image"><img src="figures/system-devices-panel.svg" class="media media-inline" alt="Power cog icon"></span></span> and
      select <span class="gui">System Settings</span>.</p></li>
<li class="steps"><p class="p">
        Open <span class="gui">Universal Access</span> and select the <span class="gui">Pointing and 
        Clicking</span> tab.
      </p></li>
<li class="steps"><p class="p">
        Switch <span class="gui">Simulated Secondary Click</span> on.
      </p></li>
</ol></div></div></div>
<p class="p">
    You can change how long you must hold down the left mouse button before it 
    is registered as a right click. On the <span class="gui">Pointing and Clicking</span> tab, 
    change the <span class="gui">Acceptance delay</span> under <span class="gui">Simulated Secondary 
    Click</span>.
  </p>
<p class="p">
    To right-click with simulated secondary click, hold down the left mouse 
    button where you would normally right-click, then release. The pointer fills 
    with blue as you hold down the left mouse button. Once it is entirely blue, 
    release the mouse button to right-click.
  </p>
<p class="p">
    Some special pointers, such as the resize pointers, do not change colors. 
    You can still use simulated secondary click as normal, even if you don't get 
    visual feedback from the pointer.
  </p>
<p class="p">
    If you use <span class="link"><a href="mouse-mousekeys.html" title="Click and move mouse pointer using the keypad">Mouse Keys</a></span>, this also allows 
    you to right-click by holding down the <span class="key"><kbd>5</kbd></span> key on your keypad.
  </p>
</div>
